<node TEXT="OpenGL loading libraries" ID="ID_243530411" CREATED="1353181304092" MODIFIED="1353183449230"><richcontent TYPE="NOTE">

<html>
  <head>
    
  </head>
  <body>
    <p>
      <font face="sans-serif" size="13px" color="rgb(0, 0, 0)">OpenGL loading libraries handle the loading of OpenGL functions. Loading OpenGL Functions is an important task for initializing OpenGL after creating an OpenGL context. This is where the role of a Loading Library comes into play. Querying the function pointers requires using a function not defined by the OpenGL API. It is a platform-specific function, and the different versions have different semantics. </font>
    </p>
    <p>
      
    </p>
    <p>
      <font size="13px" face="sans-serif" color="rgb(0, 0, 0)">An OpenGL Loading Library is a library that loads pointers to OpenGL functions at runtime, i.e. they provide access to the GL entrypoints. Some Loading Libraries like GLEW loads pointers to both core and extension functions; others like gl3w only loads the core entrypoints. </font>
    </p>
    <p>
      
    </p>
    <p>
      <font size="13px" face="sans-serif" color="rgb(0, 0, 0)">This is required to access functions from OpenGL versions above 1.1 on most platforms. </font>
    </p>
    <p>
      
    </p>
    <p>
      <font size="13px" face="sans-serif" color="rgb(0, 0, 0)">Extension loading libraries also abstracts away the difference between the loading mechanisms on different platforms. </font>
    </p>
    <p>
      <font size="13px" face="sans-serif" color="rgb(0, 0, 0)">Most extension loading libraries override the need to include gl.h at all. Instead, they provide their own header that must be used. Most extension loading libraries use code generation to construct the code that loads the function pointers and the included headers. </font>
    </p>
    <p>
      
    </p>
    <p>
      <font size="13px" face="sans-serif" color="rgb(0, 0, 0)">For information about manually loading libraries see http://www.opengl.org/wiki/Load_OpenGL_Functions </font>
    </p>
  </body>
</html>
</richcontent>
<node TEXT="GLEW (Extension Wrangler library)" FOLDED="true" ID="ID_1834171528" CREATED="1351911013424" MODIFIED="1353184445448" LINK="http://glew.sourceforge.net/"><richcontent TYPE="NOTE">

<html>
  <head>
    
  </head>
  <body>
    <p>
      <font color="rgb(0, 0, 0)" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif">The OpenGL Extension Wrangler Library (GLEW) is a cross-platform open-source C/C++ extension loading library. </font>
    </p>
    <p>
      
    </p>
    <p>
      <font color="rgb(0, 0, 0)" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif">GLEW provides efficient run-time mechanisms for determining which OpenGL extensions are supported on the target platform. OpenGL core and extension functionality is exposed in a single header file. </font>
    </p>
    <p>
      
    </p>
    <p>
      <font color="rgb(0, 0, 0)" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif">GLEW has been tested on a variety of operating systems, including Windows, Linux, Mac OS X, FreeBSD, Irix, and Solaris. </font>
    </p>
    <p>
      
    </p>
    <p>
      <font color="rgb(0, 0, 0)" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif">As of December 2012, the latest release of GLEW (1.9.0) contains support for OpenGL 4.3 and the following extensions: </font>
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <font color="rgb(0, 0, 0)" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif">OpenGL extensions </font>
      </li>
      <li>
        <font color="rgb(0, 0, 0)" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif">WGL extensions </font>
      </li>
      <li>
        <font color="rgb(0, 0, 0)" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif">GLX extensions </font>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </body>
</html>
</richcontent>
